<user>102918253898437847981<//user><username>Rodney S<//username><time>1568592115728</time><rate>5</rate><text>At last, I don't have to sail the 7 seas for a 7 leaves.  For a 7 Leaves has opened, just blocks away from me.

Occupying the former location of a non-drive thru Starbucks, this 7 Leaves Caf√© usurps the title of closest in proximity to me from the 7 Leaves on Artesia/Norwalk.  That location has a drive thru and is always busy, anytime of day.  Parking is usually hard to come by.  That may have been why Cauldron Ice Cream, the neighbor next door, probably left for the 99 Ranch marketplace on Pioneer.  Fortuitous for me, when I saw the sign for "7 Leaves Caf√© Opening Soon" in Cerritos, I was thrilled I now didn't have to fight for parking and how conveniently close it would be.

Those looking for some goodies to munch on,7 Leaves Caf√© has strawberry croissants & an assortment of macarons to choose from.

For our inaugural visit to 7 Leaves Caf√© Cerritos, we went with large mung bean & taro milk tea (easy ice/easy sugar)

Galaxy's Edge green milk?  7 Leaves' mung bean milk tea puts it to shame, and costs half as much!

Even though they were made to be easy on the sugar, I still found the drinks to be almost too sweet, for my preference.  Less so for the taro.  I'd probably ask for easy on the easy sugar (easier sugar?) next time. Regardless, both drinks were quite refreshing on a hot end of summer day.

Service was good.  Even though there was a line about 7 deep, it seemed to go by quickly & efficiently.  A few tables to occupy inside & al fresco, 7 Leaves Caf√© is rather quaint, so not a place for large groups.

Parking is via a private lot, with 7 Leaves Caf√© next to Jumbo Wok & in front of Caesar's Mongolian BBQ.

Make like a tree, and leave!  To 7 Leaves, if you're a thirsty, parched tree, that is.  I've been a fan since I first went to the Cypress location, and now I can be a closer fan, thanks to the new Cerritos location.  All the drinks are on point, and I have designs to try a couple or 10 of the various macarons, and perhaps a strawberry croissant.  Then, drown them all away with one of their delicious drinks on the menu.

Highly recommend!
NOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOM</text><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< Resp>

<gmap_id>0x80d9553bac427997:0x874d419f256ec7af<//gmap_id>< Review>
I had a wonderful experience at Stuart Benjamin & Co. I had a small diamond fall out of my engagement ring - the prong didn't break, but rather the diamond itself had never sat correctly. There was always a little gap and a skewed prong, and though I asked several jewelers if they could fix it, the answer was always no.
I came to Stuart Benjamin & Co hoping just for the replacement diamond - and upon looking at it, was told by Jeff that they would make sure to rebuild the prong entirely so this wouldn't happen again - no prompting, and none of the concern of the other jewelers I had spoken to. The diamond shape itself is antique, so they let me know they had to source the diamond and it might take a few weeks.
A week later, the perfect diamond had been found, the price they offered to fix it was so low I thought I had heard incorrectly, and they let me know it would be ready that evening.

Honestly, my ring looks better than it did the day I received it - all prongs sit perfectly, no gaps, I feel completely confident that I won't have any more missing diamonds for a long time - and if something were to happen I know exactly who I would go to.

Thanks so much for the fabulous service, fair prices, and honest interactions. I've found my local jeweler!!< /Review>

< review>
This nature center is open.. good spot to educate your children and yourself.
Can stop by and have lunch outside which has picnic tables under trees for shade.. outside are areas were live animal's are kept in captivity..Such as several turtles,red tail hawk,, owl,, racoons,,and other animals.. inside the museum are live Snakes such as King snakes, rat snakes gopher snake & a rosey boa snakes.also Tarantulas.. display of various taxidermied animals displayed throughout the museum.
Including a gift shop. The associates that work here have great attitudes and friendly..the bathrooms here are very well Maintained with tissues & soap for hygiene care.. the trails here are full of reptiles,,my advice were high laced boots cus there's Snakes around the whole nature center including rattle Snakes and other creatures that blend in with the terrains here throughout the trails . this nature center here @ Whittier Narrows is safe to visit even though homeless have been seen to gather in the trails...the El Monte Police pass through here on a regular basis which makes it more safe for visitors.. come check it out with the young ones,, I'm sure they'll be surprised to see the live animals & reptiles kept in captivity..pack a lunch with some refreshments and snacks for kids and spend a day here and the Whittier Narrows Recreation Area which is located across the street from the Whittier Narrows Nature center..
Enjoy and always be aware of your surroundings and be safe..< /review>

<username>Mike Nolan< /username>< Review>
I have had several positive experiences at the US HealthWorks facility. It is a busy place, with limited resources but, based on my experiences in several Emergency Rooms in the East Bay, they wait times and turn around times are much better here. Because this is an Urgent Care facility, the staff here must make judgment calls and set priorities based on need and level of severity. It would understandable if someone came to an urgent care facility for a test or exam and was asked to wait while others with more pressing health issues were seen first. I found the staff to be tolerant and understand and very responsive to being positive and patient. The doctors and staff at any urgent care facility are under constant pressure and stress. A little bit of understanding and willingness to work with them and appreciate their situation can go a long way to getting yourself taken care of in a timely fashion. I would recommend this
US HealthWorks facility to anyone who is in need of care.< /Review>

< review>
I decided to give Shift a try after hearing good things about the ease of buying a car here but it was extremely hard to communicate with anyone there during the whole process.

After requesting the test drive, I also entered my old vehicle for an evaluation for a trade-in. I received text messages asking me to confirm the test drive. I replied as instructed but there were no confirming messages saying they got my response. I had received emails confirming the test drive that instructed me to reply to the email if any questions so I replied but no answer either so I called them. I was put on hold for over 40 minutes before I hung up. I tried calling two more times the next two days after also emailing again. Both times I had to hold for over 20-30 minutes and no one picked up. No email replies either so I sent a Tweet to them but no response.

The acquisition team called me about my trade-in so I requested them to have a sales person call me figuring it would be easier for a Shift worker to contact another Shift department. Since then I had received another text asking me to confirm the appointment for which I replied affirmative but received no response indicating my test drive was confirmed so I was getting nervous.

I logged into the Shift dashboard to make sure everything looked correct.

Finally a sales person called back and I was assured that my test-drive was confirmed and that they would do a trade-in evaluation too at the same time. I also asked them to match a price on the same car I found listed on another site for a lower price. He said he would get approval from a manager the next morning which I was fine with.

The next morning he did confirm he got approval from a manager that they would match the lower price. I also asked him to confirm that they would do the trade-in evaluation too at the time of the test drive.

The test drive person arrived right on time and had even called me before he left Shift. Great. Test drive went well but when I mentioned the evaluation, no one had told him about it. Also when I mentioned the price match, it wasn't in his system yet either. He had the notes on it but needed to contact someone at Shift who then needed to contact another manager to approve the already manager-approved price from that morning (which was in the notes). We waited over 45 minutes for someone to re-approve the price.

The evaluation wasn't done either or I would have missed out on the $200 extra so I had to reschedule it for the delivery date of the vehicle.

We put a deposit on the car meaning we had 3 days to schedule a delivery and finish the transaction or they would release the car and we would lose our deposit. After the first weekday of the 3-day hold no one contacted us with the next steps even after I called Shift to check on it. This time someone did answer the phone but told me someone would have to call me back and that they would get to me soon. I got nervous because now I have 2 days to get the money instead of 3. They finally called back on the 2nd day with full instructions and I scheduled the delivery. After scheduling the delivery of the vehicle I got emails and text messages saying my "test drive" was confirmed. I was less nervous this time knowing that the Shift system might just not be accurate. I also asked the person delivering the car to confirm that he would do an evaluation too.

At the delivery the person again was great but when it came time to do the loan paperwork, it took over 45 minutes of waiting for someone at Shift to approve and send out the documents we needed to sign. He says normally it doesn't take this long. The whole delivery process took over 2 hours for tasks that took only about 45 minutes.

They don't fully communicate with their employees all details. I would not recommend them to any friends or neighbors looking for a smooth car-buying process. Even for the referral fee I had to find extra proof on their site I was eligible before they approved it.</review>

<Name>Christiana Roverso< /Name>< Text>
PART 1 OF 2 If you want to read about the buying process all the way down to the return process, just about every process besides selling your vehicle to shift, then you came to the right review. The one star only goes to the few individuals I feel did their job correctly, Manager Andrew, Cymantha customer service rep and another customer service rep who transferred me to Andrew.

I'll start at the beginning. This was my first time at Shift, I had been referred by my uncle who used to work there. Upon my first visit, I test drove a 2014 Nissan Leaf S, all electric vehicle with 91.8k miles, the drive was really smooth, but it did not seem like the person helping me at all had any knowledge about the vehicle except on how power is converted from AC to DC. There was no previous information about the car provided to me, it almost felt like it was just up to customers to find out about the car rather than the sales person actually giving information on the vehicle, the history especially since it is used.

The signing process took FOREVER. I arrived at 1pm on a Tuesday, and did not leave until 4pm on the basis that I had to reapply for financing with a co-signer. I asked the original rep how long this process would take should I be approved and I was told "we should be able to get everything finished today" by the gentleman who was helping me. That original rep didn't even get back to me to let me know we will have to wait to hear word from finance department until tomorrow, there was no follow up text what-so-ever apologizing for the delay and it was RIDICULOUS that I had to be the one to follow up with the rep to ask for an update rather than the other way around. The only response I got was "they aren't getting back to me, try calling the customer service number on the back of the card to see if they get back to you" WOW. I did that, and I got NO answer.

Next day, Wednesday. How long should it usually take for finance to let you know if you are approved for the loan or not? In this case, it took them almost 24 hours to get back to me, and STILL I had to be the one to call directly and speak with someone higher up to get an answer. Turns out I did get approved, but no one communicated that to me, WHY DID NO ONE COMMUNICATE THAT TO ME?! until I called and bypassed the original rep who was "helping me". I'm not that petty to even post names.

Furthermore about the car, I learned the hard way to do more research before even making a decision, but honestly I should have asked, but also it shouldn't completely be on be because the rep should have provided me information on the car without me even asking, including the history of the vehicle, and things it is known for AKA the fact that the battery needed to be replaced since it was reaching the 100k mark! I read that it costs $5k-$8k to replace the battery on 2014 Nissan Leaf S and that they should be replaced every 100K miles, which the vehicle already had 91.8k miles on it. No WONDER the battery was draining sooo quickly. I was also given an incorrect number of miles on how long it lasts on a full charge which I was told 80 miles, turns out this specific vehicle fully charged only lasts 60 miles and boy do those go quickly especially with a 91k old electric battery! I showed up at 6pm that next day to finish signing paperwork and by that time someone else was helping me who simply refused to pronounce my name correctly the ENTIRE time. He was nice, but wow, you can't even pronounce my name right? I mean, the disrespect....... (to be continued)

<Rating>4< /Rating><Text>I was in the market for a used red Miata with soft top. Timeline:

Sat late eve: I see a car with my specs on the shift.com, AutoTrader, yada yada

Sun morn: I call them first thing at 8 am. Wait time 10 mins. The lady is super professional and answers all questions. I book a test drive between noon and 2 pm. The car is off the market for 4 hours before the test drive window and 2 hours after. So my test drive takes the car off-market until 4 pm, which is great!

Sun afternoon: The car arrives within window. It's a little dusty, which makes details hard to see. We see some more damage than documented. I test drive the car and decide to buy it. Shift takes $200 off for the additional scuffs. I pay the $250 deposit to hold the car and schedule delivery for Thu eve.

Mon-Thu morn: I arrange for funds and get a cashier's check

Thu eve: Car arrives within window. All clean and shiny. Some more scuffs get revealed. Shift takes off another $150. The paperwork is a drag and takes nearly two hours because they misspell my name and have to correct it. The delivery guy also doesn't fill up the gas tank as he was running late, so he goes to the nearest gas station to fill it up during the transaction before I hand him the check. He also forgets the coveted Shift sticker too. Anyhoo, the car is mine by 6 pm.

Friday morn: I bring the car to my independent mechanic. They say it's a 'good car', 'clean', 'battery is good', 'all good'. Deal closed. _/|\_

Sat eve: The $150 refund check is in my mailbox! :raised-hands

Moral of the story: Give Shift a chance. You might just get a great car.

Room for improvement for Shift:
- While I was taking to the lady on Sun morn, I moved the delivery window by an hour (while still over the phone with her). A new confirmation text with the new time window never arrived. The confirmation email seemed to suggest that the window was not updated. But the driver did arrive within the updated window.
- Make sure the car is clean at the time of test drive, so that all the details can be seen. This would avoid surprises/disappointments at purchase time.
- The test drive driver "disqualified" my car from trade-in because the engine oil was too high. For context, I get my car regularly serviced and it drives great. Also, after he left, I got an email about the trade-in, which was very confusing.
- On the day of the sale, the delivery person was kinda slow and tired and took a long time. He hadn't had a chance to eat lunch either, so we gave him a Cliff bar. Our experience with him has lots of room for improvement for Shift.
- Re. trade-in, I got another email from Shift before the offer was set to expire. So did they really disqualify my car? Regardless, the offer was super low, so I decided to sell it privately.<//Text>< Time>

Couple of my friends sold their cars to shift.com during September 2020 and I heard great things about this company. That's why I never expected my experience would leave bad taste in my mouth when I wanted to sell my vehicle in December 2020. I guess a lot has changed during last three months.

This is my experience:
1. The Shift appraised price was USD 300 below the lowest KBB dealer value. It's for a Toyota Camry 2017 with 38K on odometer. I was driving the car regularly. The vehicle had all servicing done. Tires were changed last year. So, I did not expect that price from Shift

2. Shift's appraised value was lower than Carmax apprised value!! Just the day before shift's appointment, I went to Carmax and got my car appraised. So, I am not talking random numbers.
Additionally, Carmax gives you a week for the appraised price. So, you can probably save money if you need a rental car for a week.
Note to Shift: if your apprised price is lower than Carmax, then probably you need to worry!

That being said, I sold the car to shift for the following reasons.
1. I am moving out of the country so wanted to get this chapter closed
2. With same day pick up (USD 200) and referral bonus (USD 100) for shift, the final dollar amount was USD 100 more than Carmax. I wish Carmax had these benefits.
3. It just made economic sense to me to sell the car at this point. But, there's a difference between great and bad experience. I would rather suggest them to sell the car to the private party. I just felt like I was dealing with another car dealership.

< review>
The headache free way to sell your car! The online tool provides an estimate of what you may get before you agree to meet up for the trade in. Shift sends e mail, texts and calls to ensure you have the required documents on trade in day.

<Rating>1<//Rating><review>We bought a used Sienna in Feb 2020. When we got home, we learned that one of the passenger windows was broken and wedged in place (rigged so that it wouldn't fall into the door!), that the wing window seal had been shoved into place so that it would close (could only be intentional), and that there was a small chip in the windscreen. Yes, we should have caught all of these before purchase.

The good news is that we returned the car, which they promptly picked up.

The bad news is that they kept the car for 10 days with constantly changing estimates for the return. And, it came back dirty, by which I mean not even vacuumed or wiped, with large debris from the windscreen repair on the dash and window seal on several seats and towers behind the seats. We rejected the car. They brought it back several days later, wiped down and quickly washed, but certainly not "detailed" as promised. After serious deliberation, we accepted the car but with significant misgivings about the company.

Although the Shift concept is great, the execution, managerial oversight, and quality control are less than abysmal. Throughout the return, they repeatedly over-promised and under-delivered in promptness and quality. It appears to us that Shift's cultural strategy does not result in employees who feel a vested interest in quality or the company's reputation. To be clear, this is a managerial and cultural problem, not the fault of the young, optimistic employees they hire.

If you buy from Shift, approach their slick manner with skepticism.< /review><gmap_id>0x808f7e1ad25bd9eb:0x9caafaa524bd033c<//gmap_id>< user_id>

<user_name>Sourabh Deshmukhe< /user_name>< Text>
The worst customer experience one could have. I sold my car to Shift on Dec 23, 2019. While dropping off the car, I was never told about a 24 hour conditional sale/ cancellation period. However, since I signed the contract, I take full ownership and understand the 24 hour cancellation period. The 24 hour period however ends on Dec 24 at 6 pm.

On Thursday Dec 26, around 5 pm (which is essentially end of day on thursday) I was contacted to tell the car has a repair on the frame near the wheel and hence they can no longer buy the car. This puts me in a situation where I have to sell the car within a day since I have an international trip coming up on Sunday Dec 29 which they are well aware of. They not only violated the 24 hour period that they have cited in the agreement but also very conveniently argue that they are only supposed to complete the inspection within 24 hours and there is no time limit on when they need to inform the customer. This is a typical example of a corporation interpreting the agreement to their advantage. Shift is trying to tell me they can exercise the right to cancel unilaterally and inform me anytime after the 24 hour period. Good job! I would certainly not recommend anyone to sell/buy their car from shift as they will mend the agreement to their advantage at any given time and have no sense of customer experience.

I was as transparent as I can be and clearly mentioned to them that the wheels of the car were stolen 2 years ago and had to be replaced and hence the repair.

Here are the terms stated in their agreement:

Clause 3:

Owner acknowledges and agrees that the sale of the Vehicle from Owner to Shift is subject to Shift‚Äôs right to
inspect the Vehicle within the 24 hour period after the Pickup Date (the ‚ÄúInspection‚Äù and such 24 period, the
‚ÄúConditional Sale Period‚Äù) and to cancel the sale and return the Vehicle to the Owner if Shift determines in its sole
discretion that any of the material issues listed in Exhibit A are present (the ‚ÄúCancellation Right‚Äù). In the event
that Shift determines, in its sole discretion, during the Conditional Sale Period, that any of the material issues set
forth on Exhibit A are present, Shift will inform Owner that Shift is exercising its right to cancel the sale and not
purchase the Vehicle from Owner.Should Shift exercise its Cancellation Right and elect not to purchase the
Vehicle, the Vehicle will be returned to Owner and this Agreement will terminate.

Clause 4 :
"From and after the Purchase, Shift shall
own all right title and interest in and to the Vehicle, and shall be permitted to sell the Vehicle to any Buyer. If Shift
does not exercise the Cancellation Right during the Conditional Period, the Vehicle Purchase transaction shall be
final and irrevocable, and following the Purchase, Owner shall have no further rights, title or interest in or to the

<Review>I sold my 2017 Chevy Volt through Shift and had a great experience.  Before choosing Shift, I brought it to a traditional dealership, which offered $23,500 and VROOM, which offered 24K.  After doing my own research, I estimated that if I put in a substantial amount of my own time and energy into having the car detailed and selling it myself, I *might* be able to pocket 26K.  I knew that I would not have the capacity to do this myself, so I chose Shift.  It sold within 1 week of listing, and I pocketed 24.9K, which I considered to be a very good trade-off considering the work involved with selling a car.  I received the money within a few days of the car being sold.

There was one very minor hiccup that I hope Shift will resolve in the future with better training.  When Shift came to pick up my car, I followed the instructions of the Shift agent to sign over the title to them, but I ended up missing a signature.  Shift sent the title to me overnight via Fed-Ex with a pre-prepared return label to get the additional signature, so we were able to resolve it pretty quickly and easily.

Ultimately, I would recommend Shift without reservations if you are interested in selling your car.</Review>< pictures>

< review>
The current outbreak influenced my decision to buy a car online.  I mentioned to Ryan, my concierge, that I initially wanted to lease a Volvo XC40 or buy again from the same dealership (Mazda Dublin) because of my great experience with one of the agents there.  I actually sent the inquiries a while back, but they have not been as responsive given that most if all sales dealerships are closed.

I recently had a crash (March 13th; total car wreck on a newly purchased car - two weeks only) and really needed a car ASAP to be able to go out for essentials. All online deliveries were delayed by almost a week.  My husband was pretty much walking to the nearest grocery store to buy supplies.

One, I enjoyed the fact that I did not have to go out and spend a day at a dealership with my toddler in tow. Two, everything was done under 2 hours, unlike your traditional car-buying and actually the fact I had some visibility on the lenders were great.  I got a good deal, better than the APR provided to me by my previous dealership (but the best one was with Ford actually, at 0% just because they had their own financing company). Three it was available when I needed it most and everything was done simultaneously, me paying online, loan approval and all documents signed through docusign (this is what I expect given how tech- savvy we are nowadays).

I did find some rock chips all over the car. I will definitely need to buy some paint to fix it. That's the only downside I can think at the moment.  They did offer to connect me with customer support. I declined given the current shelter-in-place. But I think they just need to be cognizant that cars need to be pristine when it goes out for a test drive because customers can buy on the spot. Other than that experience was pretty smooth.</review>

< Text>

<rating>5</rating>< review>
I have actually been on the market for a new vehicle for the last year and a half. Talk about commitment issues..lol! Anyway on a Tuesday I went to a dealership and test drove a Chevy Equinox. Figured all the financing, etc. Was going to take the evening to think about it. Had gathered all my financials because I was pretty set on the vehicle. Then the salesman had to hand me over to a coworker as he was going to be off the next couple days. Wednesday I was bombarded with texts from this new guy whom kept trying to sell me other vehicles and what was even worse was he was running my credit for every vehicle. I was irritated. So Wednesday night I went onto Shift and found something I liked that was well within what I needed even more than I needed. Pre-qualified for a loan and set up my test drive for Friday that week. In the meantime I asked a couple friends whom had the same vehicle how they liked it and heard nothing but rave reviews. Looked up the vehicle Carfax and looked online at some other reviews.

Come Friday, during my lunch the vehicle was brought to me of course. Chris Yee was my concierge and he couldn't have been nicer or more pleasant to work with. As soon as I got behind the wheel told him to start the paperwork because not only was this test drive not going to take 30 minutes but I had already made up my mind. Within an hour and a half the car was mine. I am now a proud owner of a 2017 Dodge Journey with only 33k miles and well within my budget even with the gap insurance and the extra maintenance package I tacked on.

I think this is how I will purchase all my cars moving forward. Painless and pleasant. Thanks Shift!<//review>

We place a hard credit inquiry in order to be compliant with our lenders and secure a loan for your purchase. We understand this may seem alarming, but not to worry, credit bureaus understand that while you're shopping around for a vehicle, there may be a sudden increase in inquiries. Typically, if you purchase a vehicle within 30 days of these inquiries, they should condense into one pull and not reflect as multiple. In addition to this, if you go through a pre-approved process, there is no hard credit inquiry, as you were already pre-approved for the loan amount and no additional information is needed. <Review>Sold my car to Shift in Sacramento, CA.
First time using this service.
I had a 2016 Nissan Altima with 16k Mileage. Very clean car with no scratch (inside or outside).
KBB estimate was $16500
Received offer from TrueCar, CarMax, and Shift while listing in Craigslist for $16k.
No activity in Craigslist.
CarMax : $13000
TrueCar: $13400
Shift: $14,300 + ($150)

Dropped the car in their office myself ($50 credit)
Sold at the first appointment ($100 credit)

Some notes to keep in mind:

1- The first offer you get is the maximum possible offer they give you.

2- Call them after first offer and have them run your VIN and after couple hours you get the revised offer ( mine was the same as my car title was clean)

3- They take about 20-30 minutes to go over your car and check everything ending with 2 miles test drive and give you third and final offer ( mine remained the same as my car was super clean and still under warranty)

4- They require a 24 hours grace period and they will return your car if there is a body/frame damage.

5- You have to trust them that you will receive your money in your bank within 5 business days (mine landed in my account in 2 days)</Review><pics>None< /pics>< Resp>

<review>Very easy, low pressure car buying experience. Excellent customer service. I would recommend giving them a look if you are in the market for a new car. I had my eye on a 3 series for about a month on their site. I decided to finance the cost of the car through Shift, minus what I was willing to put as a down payment. The financing was pretty seamless and an easy process. I had a choice of rates from different lenders and choose the one that fit my needs.

Once I completed financing, I scheduled to test drive the car the same day down in Fremont.  Communication was good from the sales team at Shift. I received a call from my consierge, Eric, comfirming my test drive. Said I would arrive before the scheduled test drive time. Eric said it would be no problem.

There was a minor hiccup that came up, but it was not a deal breaker for me, because the Shift team quickly made it right, and I also had blocked out a chunk of time to see the car. While on my way, I got a call that the car I was scheduled to test drive was not at the Fremont lot and that the rest drive would have to be rescheduled.

Not wanting to have to Lyft back to Oakland, I decided to call Eric and see if they could locate the car and bring it to the Fremont location. Eric was very apologetic and said he would be in touch with his manager about getting the car to Fremont. Eric was transparent that it would likely take some time. I told him not to worry because I was not in a rush, and I was also very interested in the car.

Once I arrived to the Fremont location, I met Eric and he was able to give me an update on the car. Long story short, the Shift folks found the car and I was able to test drive it about 40 min after my scheduled appointment time. Again, not a huge deal for me because they made it right, but I understand how this could be frustrating for another person who may not have had as much time to kill. Overall, I was pleased with how well they communicated with me through the process and really stepped up their customer service to fix their mistake.

At no point during the test drive did Eric try to "sell" me the car. He simply answered any questions I had and gave me as much time as I needed to examine the car. Very low pressure. I ended up purchasing the car on the spot and they gave me a $150 credit off the price of the car for getting it the same day. The contract process was quick and easy. A member of their fiance team took the time to answer all my questions and go through the contract throughly. I'm very happy with the car the whole experience with Shift in providing a unique and comfortable car buying experience.<//review>< pics>

<text>Shift helped me find a buyer for my 2014 BMW M5. They had my vehicle inspected, took care of the detailing, photos and delivery to the new buyer. <Review>Attempting to buy a car through Shift was a terrible, frustrating experience. Shift is an amateur operation.

1. The service area advertised on the website is not the actual service area. After inputting a city online and having the location accepted, I was later told on the phone that it was outside of the service area, and that I'd have to go farther to test drive the car.

2. My scheduled test drive was cancelled due to a "mechanical problem" with the car on the day of the test drive. Not only was this extremely inconvenient and a waste of my time, it cast doubt on their whole operation, as supposedly all the cars are carefully checked via their inspection. Since the inspection Shift performs is in-house, it's not independent. And Shift does not allow independent inspections during the test drive.

3. There was no follow up besides being asked if I was interested in a different car (I wasn't). I continued to see the car I WAS interested in listed for sale, so I followed up a week later to see what the problem had been and if I could still test drive the car (e.g., if it was a battery problem, then it's no big deal). It turns out the problem was a loose mud flap (which is not a mechanical problem anyway), and was apparently since fixed, so I made a second appointment for a test drive.

4. The car never materialized for the second appointment--we were stood up. When I called the driver who was scheduled to meet us, he told me he'd been reassigned in a different city and to call Shift headquarters. <userid>110565393933507443055<//userid>< username>
Caitlin Brown</username>
<Time>1521503749839< /Time><Rating>1</Rating>< Review>
This review details my extremely negative experience selling my car with Shift.

Shift states on its website that: "Our goal is to turn what is universally regarded as a burdensome life event into a delightful experience, and to bring trust and simplicity to the peer-to-peer used car market." Its three principles are convenience, value, and trust. In my case, none of these principles were met.

When Shift makes an offer on your car, it lays out a couple different pricing options. For the purposes of this review, I'll briefly explain the guaranteed or fixed price option and the shared upside option. In the fixed price option, the seller is guaranteed a fixed price minus repair costs--the price the car actually sells for does not matter. In the shared upside offer, the seller is given a listing price, a lower guaranteed price than the fixed price offer, and the ability to split any amount above the guaranteed price that the car sells for, minus repair costs.

I made the decision to go with the fixed price offer because the list price for my car was $7,400 and in my risk assessment I did not think the potential benefit of an additional $500 possible but not guaranteed under the shared upside offer was worth the risk of actually getting less than the fixed price offer. Had Shift listed my car for $7,400 and sold it for $7,400 that would have been the end of that. I might have been slightly disappointed that I hadn't taken the risk because it would have paid off, but I would have recognized that I had made that risk calculation. That's not what happened.

Shift listed my car for $7,950 and sold it for $7,950. Had this listing price been shared with me, I would have taken the shared upside offer. As my original offers stood, the maximum fee/commission to Shift would have been $2,000. But because Shift increased the listing price the commission/fee went up to $2,550.

Nothing was disclosed about the fact that Shift could list my car for a significantly higher price. It is a bait and switch to low-ball the listing price and then increase it when Shift knew that I chose to take the fixed price offer. This is not acceptable.

After waiting weeks to hear back from customer service, Shift added a nominal sum to my payment. I would strongly recommend against selling your car with Shift.< /Review>

1502754221720</date>
<Rate>1< /Rate>< Text>
I rarely feel compelled to write a review but in this instance I want to caution all buyers on my experience with Shift SF.  Following is my experience and a few tips:

1. DO NOT TRUST THEIR INSPECTION REPORT ONLY - TAKE THE CAR TO A LOCAL MECHANIC
Shift sold me a car with bad wheel bearings (min. $500 repair and possible further existing damage) that their so-called "200-point" inspection did not catch. The full story - I test drove a Mazda with Shift intending to purchase the car but heard an odd, minor wheel noise when the car hit around 50 mph - I requested the Shift employee to take it back for a re-inspection of the noise. Upon further inspection, they said it was a non-issue and I trusted them, purchasing the car. Skeptical, I took the car the next day to a trusted local mechanic to confirm the wheel noise was ok. The mechanic knew after just a 2 minute drive that the wheel bearings are bad (typically happens only with cars triple the mileage) possibly from a large pothole or curb hit.

While Shift followed true to their 5 day/200 mile return guarantee, I would be highly skeptical of the thoroughness and quality of their mechanics as a scaling start-up. Make sure you take a Shift car into an independent mechanic!

Just as frustrating, against Customer Service 101, they seem to have no intention to offer service recovery/compensation for the hours spent purchasing a broken, misrepresented vehicle.

2. DO NOT EXPECT DEALERSHIP LEVEL TELEPHONE SUPPORT
They have serious issues with telephone support with both their Sales and Buyer Support offices not picking up their phones during weekdays. With multiple follow-ups needed on the car inspection and payments during my purchasing process, it was extremely hard to get in touch with them. A traditional dealership, while often pestering, is much more responsive and reliable.

3. DOUBLE CHECK YOUR BANK ACCOUNT IF YOU ARE DOING ACH TRANSFER
They also had an issue with an ACH transfer from one of my bank accounts. Luckily, I had a backup account to pay from - double check that your account will work for ACH transfer to Shift.</Text>

<Rate>5</Rate>< review>
I sold a 2011 BMW X3 through Shift a few weeks ago.  I've sold cars privately in the past, but I was going to be out of town quite a bit, so I just wanted a quick transaction.  Carmax offered me $11,000, which was just insulting.  Shift sent me an email when I put up the car on Craigslist, and after Googling them a bit, I contacted them and gave them the details on the car.  I was taking a trip that weekend, and their location is very close to SFO, so I made an appointment and dropped the car off on the way to the airport.

The man who helped me, Michael Castro, was very polite and professional.  He took the car and had it looked at then gave me the breakdown.  The guaranteed sale price was $14,000, and he thought there was a good chance it would sell for $16,000 or $17,000.  There was a mechanical issue and a minor cosmetic issue which I was aware of that they would have to fix first, at my expense (taken out of the final payment).  I agreed to have them fix the two issues and sell the car.  Michael walked me through the digital paperwork which went by very quickly.  Altogether I think I was only in the office for 30-45 minutes.  Michael got me a Lyft to take me to SFO, free of charge, which was really nice.

A few weeks later, the car sold.  It sold for $16,950, and after Shift's commission of $1,475 and the repair cost of $706 (which was reasonable) plus my $100 credit for agreeing to sell the car with them on the first visit, I promptly received a check in the mail for $14,869.  I did no work, talked to no buyers, didn't have to take any pictures, and I still got almost $4,000 more than if I had sold it to Carmax.  It was definitely the best car-selling experience I have ever had, and Shift will be my first choice the next time I have a car to sell.   I just really couldn't believe it was that easy and that I still reaped such a high price.  My experience was excellent, and I highly recommend selling your car through Shift!</review>

<date>1492020009658< /date>< Text>
3 stars only because my first experience with them was very pleasant, but they did screw up on the name on the registration, which I have to take out the time to visit the DMV to have corrected AND pay the fee for that correction. I just assumed that was an honest mistake which didn't affect my overall opinion. Because of that pleasant transaction, I didn't hesitate to return to them for my second car.
However, my second experience, I'd give them zero if I could:

At the time of test driving I specifically asked what the 30-day warranty covered..in case anything needed fixing after buying. I was clearly told that it is a "bumper-to-bumper" coverage, good for 30 days after purchase.

Make sure that you get a full description of what that 30-day warranty covers from a qualified rep before buying. Turned out that a week after buying my car from them I noticed a shimmy in the front end while breaking at higher speeds (on freeway). Not only that, but the car began to idle rough AND the air conditioner began to fail (cooled, but no where near cold like it was when we first test drove it) - clearly requiring a recharge.

Upon contacting them about these issues, (which took me a few calls & emails to finally talk with someone who was qualified to provide accurate answers), I was told that they don't cover air conditioning or breaks. What they offer is a "powertrain" coverage, which, according to their site:
"30-day, 1,000 mile limited warranty now comes standard with every Shift Certified car. A limited warranty package that will protect you in the event that the key powertrain components of your car fail.
This includes all of the critical parts that propel your car forward: your engine, transmission, drivetrain, and fuel delivery system."

I told them that I was told by one of their reps that it was a bumper-to-bumper warranty. Their response - "He shouldn't have said that. Sorry about that". They then offered me the extended warranty packages, which at first sounded good, but upon researching I decided that I didn't want it. They had no problem repeatedly contacting me via email & phone to sell me the bogus package & I told them why I didn't want it: reviews for that coverage via their agency sucked.
Clearly, they know how to make contact, but only when they're trying to sell something, while ignoring anything requiring a remedy.
They did tell me to bring the car in & they'll "check out & assess" the rough idle and would take about a week, which would leave me without a car for that period. I decided to just take my lumps as a lesson learned & take my car in to my trusted mechanic & give him the business to service & repair.

I must also mention that they screwed up on the name of the second registration, too - and again, having to visit the DMV & pay for the correct name on registration. This has lead me to realize that their line of communication is flawed somewhere between hearing & writing down the name of the person buying the car.
Save yourself the unnecessary bs - Make sure that you review what is being written down before the paperwork is submitted.< /Text>

<rating>5<//rating>< Text>
Outstanding food, friendly service, great happy hour. Lots of choices of small plates (3 till 6 M-Sat), from which we ordered half a dozen baked oysters ($6), a roasted beet salad ($3), wasabi guacamole w/wonton chips ($3), and a roll of the day (spicy tuna, $5). Everything was fresh and flavorful. Off the main menu, we ordered the northern California roll, which was also great. Their dessert menu was unique, with each dessert built from 5 or 6 components. We ordered a fruit dessert: pineapple in light tempura, lychee, strawberries, and pear in a spicy lychee sauce. So flavorful! It was one of the best meals we had in a while! The service was exceptional.<//Text>

< Text>
I've eaten sushi on both east and west coasts and at some of the best sushi bars in the world. This place is by far the best to date. < review>
Always a nice place to visit.
Unfortunately I came in a bad time to try to swim in the makeshift Lagoon..
I guess early in the season. Be careful of certain people that are doing certain illegal fishing things to take out the fish plant and the park rangers need to be aware of that.
Otherwise quiet and peaceful and still a beautiful place.
Come by in the spring or fall time especially when the weather is great and you're going to have a lot of open picnic tables and BBQ Pits available.
Check in with the local Rangers to make sure you can do that.</review>

<review>Don Castro is a great place to picnic and swim when the lagoon is open. There are quite a few picnic areas scattered around the park.
There is a changing are inside the restrooms next to the lagoon entrance.
There are trails with a moderate difficulty level.
It's a hot spot for fishing and they stocked the lake recently (April 2019) with 750 lb of trout. Day permits are $5.
There is a $5 fee to park on most weekends in the summer and major holidays (except Thanksgiving/Christmas). It's free during weekdays.
If the park were bigger, had more to see or do, I'd rate it higher.</review><Pictures>None</Pictures>< response>

< UserId.>
117529090771883983076</UserId.>
<Name>Yevonne Williams< /Name><Time>1531167066821< /Time><rating>4< /rating>< text>
This Hidden Gem is an Local Favorite for swimming, fishing, barbeques, parties and hiking. The lake is very clean and always has adequate Life Gaurds on staff as well as Park Rangers and Cleaning Staff. The bathrooms and showers are large and there are plenty of very large changing stalls that can accommodate a parent and several small children. The snack bar isn't always open but most people pack coolers, picnics and barbecues. There are covered areas that can be reserved but many people bring their own pop ups and tents. There is a wonderful family atmosphere. Not only is the entrance handicapped accessible, there is a ramp that can take a wheelchair all the way down to the lake.

The lake was stocked with 500 pounds of fish in June 2018. There is a pier but most people bring their lawn chairs and post up under the trees. A fishing permit is required and can be purchased at the entrance to the swimming area. You do have to pay to park during swim season and a large part of the parking area is unpaved. This affected my rating.

If you haven't been, or haven't been in a long time, you are in for a pleasant surprise. I highly recommend this park.<//text>

< Review>
Great and nice picnic place. There are lot of picnic area and pre designated bench available. However if you don't get one you can still go and just have you own spot near a tree or a small pond :).

We went during spring time and swimming area was not open yet, but still enjoyed a lot of nice nad open space. Also there is lot of shade so you can always get a spot you like.

All in all a good place.

< name>
Carlos Mangrobang</name>
<Time>1490407528593<//Time>< Rating>
4< /Rating>
<text>Don Castro Lake is a very difficult body of water to fish in.  Although, it is picture perfect to look at especially from the dock, because the water tends to be murky , fishing is quite challenging.  Access to water is also far from the parking lot.  Restroom facility is clean but far from the dock.  Portables are not cleaned out everyday so, it tends to look disgusting.  The facilities people are very nice and the grounds are kept pretty clean with no visible trash.  There is a lagoon that becomes accessible to the public during the summer that's probably worth a visit.  Similarly, during a scheduled fish plant, the lake generates large size catches.  Anglers are generally nice and civil to each other.  However, because the dock or the lake is small, crossing lines is very likely.  So be prepared to be confronted if you fish there.<//text><pictures>None< /pictures><Response>None<//Response>< Gmap_id>
0x808f93b2576ee8c7:0x7995aedcf984c4b7<//Gmap_id>

<GmapID>0x808f93b2576ee8c7:0x7995aedcf984c4b7</GmapID><Time>1467922255007<//Time><Rating>4< /Rating><name>Matthew Bogdanov<//name>< Review>
Went on the 4th of July and as expected tons of people were there (over a 1000 I heard). Sadly only 1 person at the gate taking tickets, so there was a constant line of 50 - 100 people to get in that took about 30 minutes to stand in line. Large area of sand and grass with shade on the outside fence. Lots of BBQ stands and tables. Lake/Pool is concrete on the bottom lined with sand. 2 levels of swimming, 1 for kids and another for swimmers deeper in. Parents are told to be near their parents at all times and lifeguards are a stickler for this (they'll go find a parent and give a lecture). Water is murky but cool.</Review>
